result.execSummary:
The defendant was charged with both OWI (2nd) and Operating w/ PAC (2nd). The defendant was found guilty of OWI (2nd) and the other charge, Operating w/ PAC (2nd) was dismissed by the court.

  • Vincent W Dixon III was found guilty of OWI (2nd), an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).
  • Vincent W Dixon III was found guilty of Bail Jumping-Felony, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(b).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Defendant to pay fine and court costs during term of probation on count 2 and 16CF12 and 14CF272.

Provided that Defendant files with the Court satisfactory documentation that he will have a Secure Continuous Remote Alcohol Monitor (SCRAM) installed at his own expense and at all times while
privileged to leave the jail during necessary and reasonable hours, the Court will grant the Defendant the privileges set forth in Wisconsin Statute Section 303.08. The Ozaukee County Sheriff has no
obligation of any kind to assist with or allow any SCRAM monitoring on this judgment; the duties and powers of the Ozaukee County Sheriff with respect to those in his custody under the Wisconsin Statutes
shall not be limited by this Judgment of Conviction in any way.

miscConds.notes: Bond of $1000 applied to restitution.  The restitution amount listed reflects an additional Administrative Cost of 10% of the amount of restitution pursuant to Section 973.06(1)(g).  The 5% Restitution Surcharge is equal to 5% of the total of the restitution, costs, attorney fees, and fines, pursuant to Section 973.20(11)(a).

If probation is revoked or discharged with outstanding financial obligations, in addition to all other enforcement sanctions available to the court, a civil judgment enforceable by all creditors' remedies shall be entered against the defendant and in favor of restitution victims and governmental entities for the balance due.
